data.text:
One Life's Tale

In ancient times, when the world was one and whole, was born a man gifted with extraordinary magic and the ability to discern the color of souls. Though he hid himself behind a veil of somberness and pride, his love for the star and its people was as pure as his snowy locks and his soul as golden as his eyes. He was blessed with a dear brother in all aspects but blood, and a most beloved friend that brought the suns light to his life. By following in his suns wake, he too earned the respect and admiration of their people, and owing to his brothers recommendation, he became a leader, even though he never considered himself anything remarkable. Together, the three of them embarked on countless journeys, and so deep was their bond, they vowed to never part even in death and rebirth.

All was well until the end of days befell the star and its people. The sacrifices to be made were too great, and his sun left his side to find another path. His brother left his side to become part of salvations sacrifice. When mankind first faced grief and despair, the sorcerer shared in their torment. And then he witnessed the gods of Dark and Light fight for days without end, until the Light split the world and every life upon it. He and two other souls were the only survivors, though not his sun nor his brother. As far as he was concerned, he was left all alone.

His world had become fourteen hollow huskshis people, malformed aberrations incapable of even forming words. The sorcerer and his two companions resolved to mend the star and the whole of mankind, no matter how long it might take. For the return of those he loved, he would pay any price, he would bear the weight of thousands of hopes, dreams and prayers. For a life without love is not worth living, and he was never one to turn his back on those in need.

The malformed fragments of his people begin to learn and evolve. But they do not recall their past, and ignorant as they are, they turn against each other. They deceive, they betray, they kill for their own selfish gain. They dare to call themselves the real mankind, and the sorcerer feels disgust and indignation at their hubris. The sundered ever skew historys weavewith haste they move through too-short lives, driven to err by base desires, toward waste and wasting on they run.

And yet, as the sorcerer walks the land and mingles with them, he can also appreciate their compassion and kindness towards each other. Their imagination, their resourcefulness, their determination to survive and forge ahead despite the unfair fate imposed on them. He does not consider them truly alivehowever, there is a spark of life in them, and so he questions his chosen course. Is it right to snuff out the light of this life, meager as it is?

The answer is not an easy one. The sorcerer decides to observe, and hopehe would measure the sundereds worth, and if they prove they can resist the temptation of giving into their selfish desires when granted the means and power, then they will be judged rightful stewards of the star. But as eons pass, again and again they fail, each calamity marking yet another tragedy. Each Rejoining wearing down the sorcerers expectations, to the point he can only see hope in the return of the lostand even that is starting to fall apart, as his fellow unsundered further lose themselves.

He holds fast to his memories, and that gives him the strength to carry on. But it has been twelve thousand years, and he is so, so unspeakably tired and lonely. So many lives lost, so many lives to savelove, hatred, resolve, doubt, pride, guilt, courage, fear, devotion, exhaustion If only he could just close his eyes, drift into sleep and never wake up. To pass the torch to a worthy successor. But there is none who may be fit to bear the mantle and the burden.

Once more, he is roused into action. Another reflection to be soon joined with the star, another calamity that will mark yet another failure for the sundered in proving him wrong. At this point, he has grown numb to the horror and the tragedy. Too many principles discarded, too many lesser evils committed in the name of the greater good. It is better to pretend these lives are worthlessit hurts less to see those around you die and die as they suffer and despair at fates cruelty.

But then, in this fragmented world nearly consumed by abhorrent Light, he gazes at those who would oppose this fate and spies a familiar huea soul that once belonged to his sun, even shattered as it is. The very idea of raising a hand against this soul shakes the sorcerer, and so he decides to give one last chance at hope. He decides to bridge the rift between them and find a new path togetherone that does not require further bloodshed. If his suns shade is capable of containing this worlds corrupted Light, then he will be most glad to lay down his arms.

The soul that once was his sun is wary at first, seeing him as an unscrupulous villain who has wrought untold misery to the world and its people. But curiosity arises amidst the mistrust, and questions are asked, respect and understanding blossom. The sorcerer, too, finds himself genuinely at ease, even daring to open his heart and share his sorrow. For the first time in forever, he tells his story, and there is someone there to listen. He sees this brave soul pass each stage of the trial and he is proud. He dreams of having his beloved friend back, at long last

But in the moment of truth, his suns radiance is blotted by accursed Light. This soul starts to shatter, and so does the sorcerers heart. He lashes out against this new disappointment, sneers at this souls imminent demise and that of this forsaken shard, but most of all, he rages against himself. For having been so weak as to believe that there was hope left for him, for them. Lies, deceit, delusionsthere is no hope in the future, so he takes the heir of Allag, the key to correcting the past. And yet a part of him still wants to reach out to this futile dream. A desperate plea that he masks as an invitation to his submarine demesneprove me wrong, show me that there is something left in this world worth fighting for. Relieve me of my burden, and let me rest from my endless wandering.

In this recreation of his lost home, he awaits. To the shade of his brother, he entrusts the stars and the sun, should he lose the coming clash, to grant peace to his remaining companion and entrust his legacy to the soul that prevailed over him. An unlikely event, but he has the wisdom of eons as to know that only fools would make provisions for victory alone. But perhaps he is a fool nonetheless, for holding onto vain hopeboth his peoples return, and his suns triumph. He cannot abandon his course, but he wants to believe A circle without end, a spiral of conflicting emotions. At the very least, he would see his suns soul off himselfand he shall yield to no one else than his sun.

He is surprised to find that this crackling souls companions have not forsaken whom is now a threat to their existence. He sees the bond between them, stalwart and unbroken, and it reminds him of the past and jealousy arises, and he lashes out against the unfairness of it all. And still, he wants them to understand. So he challenges themweather the horror of what befell my kin, witness what stole everything dear to us, and emerge victorious. A part of him wishes that the sight might awaken his suns shades memories, and thus provide the strength to contain the corruption of Light.

It does not. It is yet another disappointment, and once more, his heartbreak translates into scathing scorn. But all of a sudden, just as his suns shades radiance is about to be consumed by abhorrent Light, a miracle happensa blinding glow, and he glimpses his beloved friend. It lasts only a moment, and he tries to convince himself that his longing has betrayed his senses. But then the heir of Allag casts this invocationa spell that was only possible through the sorcerers own legacy, pillars of light surrounding this shard of his sun that stands against him. A sight that he knows so well, and yet this is all a mockeryan insult to the memory of his beloved friend that was stolen from him by cruel fate and the goddess who cursed his kin to oblivion and now forces them to fight each other. He is outraged beyond words. Trial by combat shall decide who is worthy to inherit the stardeath is what awaits the loser. For their people, for their world, they bring all to bear and face the most dangerous adversary of their livesfor they both bear the hopes, dreams and prayers of those they love, and for them, they will brave any hell and stare down Death itself.

The sorcerer acknowledges the revelation of his opponents true self and answers in kind. He casts off the mask he has worn for twelve thousand years and the title that represents his duty, and reveals his real name to his old friend and new foe. His form swells and shifts, bare truth in transformation. This has become a clash of ideals, a contest of willsa debate most brutal and quintessential.

The battle is fierce beyond description. Past the far edge of fate, ring blades Dark and Light He sees the goddess shielding his friend turned foe, and his hatred, his wrath, his grief, his pain pour out like a broken dam. He finds himself overwhelmed, this accursed auracite stifling his aether and holding him in placebut he is a sorcerer of eld, a nigh-bottomless font of magic, and he crushes it and lunges against his friend turned foe for their final clash

A most radiant axe strikes him. The pain is unbearable, but he cannot give up. He will not give up

The light is blinding, and the pain relents. The first rays of dawn rise from the horizon, and he knows it is finally over. Judgment has been passed, and his suns shade has been deemed worthy. The sorcerer merely asks for him and his kin to be remembered, that their lives might have meaning in this new future. His suns shade nods, and he knows his legacyand that of his beloved friendis in good hands. He sorrowfully smiles, wishing that things may have been different, but in the end, his sun came to save him from his griefas he had always hoped.

He surrenders to the currents of the Underworld, hoping to finally close his eyes forevermore but there, in the depths where souls and stars rest, he finds his truthmemories from a time before time erased, now restored. The nature of the apocalypse that befell the star, the knowledge that the god that is his people will be destroyed and the souls of his brother and his kin released at last, the reason for why the goddess spared him and the purpose of his wanderingbut most of all, the realization that he had already deemed the reincarnation of his sun worthy of his legacy. Perhaps, in a corner of his subconscious mind, he always knew that there was still hope.

He realizes he still has a role to play come the end, and so he watches the final chapter of this play unfold. Regardless of the reason, the actions of the goddess he cannot condone, and the pain and grief that he was cursed to bear for twelve thousand years are not something he can forgive. He will not do this for the goddess, but for the star, for life and for hopefor his suns future, for the last of his kin, he shall answer the call as he has ever done. This he does not once, but twice.

Alongside his brother, the sorcerer is called to the stage at the edge of the universe for an encore, to bear aloft the blossom of hope together in the face of despair itself. The three of them, reunited for a fleeting momentpast, present and future interwoven. A bond that shall ever transcend time and space in the form of a prayer, a wish, a promise. His suns heritors eyes are downcast at the sorcerers partingalas, he is too soft for his own goodthus he issues a challenge. Go forth, seek discovery, witness the wonders of the star and share in its peoples joys and woesas heritor to the sun and wearer of the mantle, as he once did in memory of his beloved friend. Unspoken, the promise of a reunion at journeys end.

The sorcerer gazes at his suns heritor with pride, and for the first time in eons, his smile is hopeful.

Though they again must part ways, at the very least, this time his brother is with himhe is no longer alone. All it remains to do is to wait for that fateful day in which all three of them meet again in the depths, and embark upon a new journey together. His sorrow and his sins, washed away by the tide.

Perhaps there will be more calls in the future, though he would very much prefer to sleep. Alas, he has never been able to refuse his sun. But who knows what the future might have in store? Whatever it comes to pass, his duty is done, his wandering over, and he has earned his rest, embraced by gentlest night.

As he drifts into slumber, the sorcerer ponders his truth. His answer to the question.

The suffering of ages shaped him into a man his younger self had been horrified at, when granted knowledge of his future deeds. Living through the circumstances and walking the path to his final destination makes him understand his choice, come to terms with who he is and what he has done, and the decisions he made. He does not regret it, for it was his chosen path, and his alone. He fought for love, for lifefor hope.

Whether history remembers him as a hero or a villain, it matters not. All hinges on perspective, and there is no right nor wrong. It was his life, and he lived it on his own terms.

He heard, he felt, he thought. He looked, he learned, he remembered. He stumbled and he walked. He grieved and he cherished. He wept and he rejoiced. He scorned and he honored. He harmed and he mended. He hesitated and he believed. He doubted and he trusted. He hated and he loved. He was defeated but he was invincible. And he hoped until the very end.
